no prospect of silencing. It provides case studies of a range of very different but highly articulate dissenters, focusing on their modes of political activism and on the varieties of dissenting response possible, and demonstrating the vitality and integrity of witnesses to a spectrum of post-revolutionary Protestantism. It also seeks, through an exploration of textual culture and poetic texts in particular, to illuminate both the ways in which nonconformists sought to engage with central authorities in Church and State, and the development of nonconformist identities in relation to each other. GEORGE SOUTHCOMBE is Director of the Sarah Lawrence Programme, Wadham College, Oxford.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 06. Mrz 2024) 0aDissenters, ReligiousxHistoryy17th centuryzEngland. 0aDissenters, ReligiouszEnglandxHistoryy17th century. 4aEarly Modern History. 4aEarly Modern Literature. 4aHistory of Religion. 7aRELIGION / History.2bisacsh  aChurch of England.  aNonconformist.  aNorwich.  aSheep-stealing.08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertBoydell and Brewer Complete eBook-Package 2019z978311143102440uhttps://doi.org/10.1515/9781787446199?locatt=mode:legacy40uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9781787446199423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9781787446199/original  a978-3-11-143102-4  Boydell and Brewer Complete eBook-Package 2019b2019  aGBV-deGruyter-alles